  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Sustainable Production in Native Indigenous Communities Near Lake Titicaca</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Indigenous families in the highlands of La Paz are witnessing the deterioration of their soil, the reduction of their water sources, the loss of ancestral knowledge and the implementation of deficient systems of agricultural processing and marketing.  As a result, their capacity to guarantee their families&#x2019; food security is limited. To mitigate this situation, this project will seek the participation of organized small-farmers and municipal governments. At the community level, small-farmer organizations will be strengthened, indigenous advocates will be trained, agroecological production will be promoted and camelids will be restocked. The animals will provide fleece to families for both clothing and to sell at markets. At the government level, small-farmer organizations will promote the adoption of public policies that favor communal land management, the recovery of traditional production practices and sustainable management of natural resources. During the three years of the project, 200 families will participate in the project and 200 more will participate through the Passing on the Gift process.  All the participating families live in 12 communities located in three municipalities.  In the follow-up phase, another 200 more families will benefit from Passing on the Gift.</narrative>
  </description>
